04713nam a22006015i 9781501773693DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017736937 a10.1515/97815017736932doi  a(DE-B1597)653755  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHX531b.V55 2024 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a335.001223/eng/202309061 aVinokour, Maya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWork Flows :bStalinist Liquids in Russian Labor Culture /cMaya Vinokour. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (324 p.) :b7 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNIU Series in Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction. Flow: Resource Management in the Twentieth Century -- t1. Self-Discipline and Liquid Channeling in Prerevolutionary Russian Utopianism -- t2. Energetic Flows in Fedorov, Gorky, and Bogdanov -- t3. The Organic Turn: Labor, Technology, and the Body in Early Soviet Culture -- t4. Apotheoses of the Organic Turn -- t5. Liquids in Socialist Realism I: Reactionary Romanticism -- t6. Liquids in Socialist Realism II: Three Case Studies -- t7. And Quietly Flows Platonov -- t8. “I Am a Stream of Bright Joy”: Daniil Kharms and the Liquid Language of Stalinism -- tCoda: Stalinist Flows in Postsocialism and Beyond -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWork Flows investigates the emergence of "flow" as a crucial metaphor within Russian labor culture since 1870. Maya Vinokour frames concern with fluid channeling as immanent to vertical power structures—whether that verticality derives from the state, as in Stalin's Soviet Union and present-day Russia, or from the proliferation of corporate monopolies, as in the contemporary Anglo-American West. Originating in pre-revolutionary bio-utopianism, the Russian rhetoric of liquids and flow reached an apotheosis during Stalin's First Five-Year Plan and re-emerged in post-Soviet "managed democracy" and Western neoliberalism.The literary, philosophical, and official texts that Work Flows examines give voice to the Stalinist ambition of reforging not merely individual bodies, but space and time themselves. By mobilizing the understudied thematic of fluidity, Vinokour offers insight into the nexus of philosophy, literature, and science that underpinned Stalinism and remains influential today. Work Flows demonstrates that Stalinism is not a historical phenomenon restricted to the period 1922-1953, but a symptom of modernity as it emerged in the twentieth century. Stalinism's legacy extends far beyond the bounds of the former Soviet Union, emerging in seemingly disparate settings like post-Soviet Russia and Silicon Valley.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism and literaturezRussia (Federation). 0aCommunism and philosophyzRussia (Federation). 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aPolitics and literaturezRussia (Federation). 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRussian literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aHISTORY. 4aLITERARY STUDIES. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aStalinism, social relations, relations of production, labor discourse, labor culture, Russian rhetoric of liquids, pre-Soviet cosmism, Tolstoyism, labor history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150177369340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773693423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773693/or